A week after discovering a tentative deal, both banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a per-unit price of $25.25, or $3 billion.
The agreed price is less than 19 % of the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities, which will ensure a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the global transaction would be based on a unit price of $29, or 28 percent above its current exchange rate.
Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% at $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said Juan Mack, Morgan Stanley’s chief executive officer.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow it to diversify its activities but it passes under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to behave much more prudently than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the agreement has been modified during the last days: last Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japanese for almost 8.5 billion dollars.
" A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the CEO of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, " we thought that the stake would have been composed only of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we have wished to minimize risks and hedge ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares within a year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 or less, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley says that the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to take investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined to give details on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of close to 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it has greatly eased its balance sheet since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been grueling for the group, which has seen its stock price halve as the cost of security against a risk of default on its debt soared.
This cost fell last Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the other sole “survivor” of the big Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part for Warren Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he is the third to put to the vote a project for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" received 28%, 7% of the votes were null and void and 0.7% were blank.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a tally by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory for the "yes" vote, estimating it at between 63 percent and 70 percent.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed in an overwhelming way,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in complete calm, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the " new socialism " advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution implied an increase in the power of the State over the economy, reserving for it the " development planning " of a country that lived essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good upon their arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On 19 September, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an all-terrain safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then they have moved from one place to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, flown aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," the official said.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and by members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men of the secret services, of the special forces," he said without elaborating.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an SUV on which the kidnappers were on board, of whom six were killed, including the Chadian chief and two were arrested.
It also claimed that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement, (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
Letters - Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying the current election campaign.
It's better this way.
But a sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums that are granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are starving?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government to neglect its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don’t we have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage like in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government dedicates three and a half million euros to restore only the Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage has to be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Quebec History Societies, at least 40,000 benevolent people grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned to look into history, preserve with little money heaps of private archives and preserve archaeological vestiges.
These are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and desperation when promoters and managers throw their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of the Fortis Bank.
The States of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has businesses in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the president of the European Central Bank and the head of economic competition of the European Commission.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the crisis of the Euro zone in the framework of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves more than a year ago, therefore the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense can be considered as precedents.
According to the decision taken early Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the activities - mainly insurance - bought last year from the Dutch ABN Amr<0xC3><0xB3>.
The actions of Fortis began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, this bank is too big to allow it to break.
The company’s shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to company executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp drop in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the U.S. market in relation to the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, stocks showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when viewing drug purchase data.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which the use of prescription data in all cases is linked to the approval of the given person.
It must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we entrust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and indemnity amount depend on the client’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the control.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the customer's diseases and health status.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that the level of fat in the blood is practically incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headache and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-raising factor for insurance companies while the former do not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities already force them to this, although they did not receive a fine for negligence until now.
Some companies have also developed the results of laboratory tests and combining them with drug consumption data provides more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the authority for the control of specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the individual for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person can not deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the fox’s good will.
Global menu of Marseille
EU doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocal trading partners, this issue in addition to the other mostly global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more say in international affairs but member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President of the EU, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission, and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade to more than one hundred billion euros in five years.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
Thus, the existing 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements with India were legally harmonized, so that air transport can also fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism – all forms of the latter – and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha round of trade liberalization was also urged, although both sides bear great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, i.e. until 2020 it wants to reduce pollutant emissions by at least twenty percent.
India also agrees with this, just as at next year’s climate conference a global agreement should be reached and by 2050 the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by fifty percent.
They also wished to hinder the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the deal would be for a period of 15 years.
In Frankfurt more than three hundred Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the international exhibition of the book in Frankfurt.
